&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Hi Michael,
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;biased&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; How different is what you have described from
&gt; &gt; &gt; http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus/1.4/howto_tomcat.html ?
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Actually, what you described is exactly JUnitEE
&gt; &gt; &gt; (http://junitee.sourceforge.net/).
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I agree with you, it starts simple and then you need some more
&gt; features.
&gt; &gt; &gt; For example, you need to automate the tests as part of a build (this
&gt; is
&gt; &gt; &gt; probably one of the most wanted feature). So you will start to have
&gt; a
&gt; &gt; &gt; client part that calls your URL, parses the XML and display the
&gt; result.
&gt; &gt; &gt; All is fine but then you also want to be able to execute the test
&gt; from
&gt; &gt; &gt; any of the existing JUnit integration tools (from IDEs, using Ant
&gt; junit
&gt; &gt; &gt; task, etc). So you will transform your client side into a TestCase
&gt; so
&gt; &gt; &gt; that it can be run by any test runner ...
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; ... and this is Cactus ! :-)
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; To summarise :
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; - yes Cactus can be a simple as what you describe (this is actually
&gt; a
&gt; &gt; &gt; feature of version 1.4, which is not released yet - but soon to be)
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; - it allow for more should you need it
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; - it is documented and there are resources on Cactus : website +
&gt; books +
&gt; &gt; &gt; articles
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; - BTW, Cactus integrates completely with Ant to automated start up
&gt; and
&gt; &gt; &gt; shutdown of application servers
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;/biased&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Yes, I am the original author of Cactus and thus I am biased :-) but
&gt; as
&gt; &gt; &gt; a user I would always go with existing framework if I find any that
&gt; &gt; &gt; perform what I want. For example, I wouldn&#39;t dare write my logging
&gt; &gt; &gt; framework, MVC controller one, XML to Java mapping one, etc.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; In the end it is your choice. I&#39;m just writing this email so that
&gt; you
&gt; &gt; &gt; know Cactus does what you want and that you shouldn&#39;t skip it
&gt; because
&gt; &gt; &gt; you think it doesn&#39;t.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Cheers,
&gt; &gt; &gt; -Vincent
&gt; &gt; &gt;
