&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; What you describe sounds very similar to Cactus:
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus/
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Have you looked at it?
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Yes, and what I&#39;m describing is far simpler than Cactus. There is
&gt; no
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; framework to speak of. Just a servlet that knows how to run a test
&gt; &gt; &gt; suite
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; and return the results as xml. For instance, you would pass this
&gt; URL
&gt; &gt; &gt; to
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; your browser to run the tests in a remote app server.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; http://localhost:8080/junit?classname=com.package.test.TestCase
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; It is very simple, but powerful. Since the test executes within
&gt; the
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; servlet container you can access all the facilities of the app
&gt; server.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; We&#39;ve also automated the startup and shutdown of the app server,
&gt; so
&gt; &gt; &gt; the
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; entire test process is completely scripted. This makes it simple
&gt; to
&gt; &gt; &gt; plug
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; the whole process into our cruise control build process.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Mike
